lay:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">8.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-8\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 4.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-9\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">9.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-9\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Leys, Vincent, and Daniel Bryce. Adapting to Climate Change in Coastal Communities of the Atlantic Provinces, Canada: Land Use Planning and Engineering and Natural Approaches. Mar. 2016, pp. 27. <a href=\"https://research.fit.edu/media/site-specific/researchfitedu/coast-climate-adaptation-library/canada-amp-arctic/canada---atlantic/Leys--Bryce.--2016.--CC-in-Coastal-Communities-of-the-Atlantic-Provinces,-Land-Use,-Engineering-Natural-Approaches.pdf\">https://research.fit.edu/media/site-specific/researchfitedu/coast-climate-adaptation-library/canada-amp-arctic/canada---atlantic/Leys--Bryce.--2016.--CC-in-Coastal-Communities-of-the-Atlantic-Provinces,-Land-Use,-Engineering-Natural-Approaches.pdf</a>.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-10\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">10.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-10\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Kuhnle, R. (2020). USDA. Watershed Physical Processes Research: Oxford, MS. <a href=\"https://www.ars.usda.gov/southeast-area/oxford-ms/national-sedimentation-laboratory/watershed-physical-processes-research/docs/local-scour-in-the-vicinity-of-spur-dikes/#:~:text=A%20spur%20dike%20can%20be,pools%20in%20unstable%2C%20disturbed%20streams\">https://www.ars.usda.gov/southeast-area/oxford-ms/national-sedimentation-laboratory/watershed-physical-processes-research/docs/local-scour-in-the-vicinity-of-spur-dikes/#:~:text=A%20spur%20dike%20can%20be,pools%20in%20unstable%2C%20disturbed%20streams</a>.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-11\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">11.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-11\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Steichen, J. (2020). Design Criteria for Debris Basins. <a href=\"https://extension.missouri.edu/publications/g1528\">https://extension.missouri.edu/publications/g1528</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-12\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">12.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-12\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Minnesota Pollution Control Agency. (2019). Sediment control practices - Check dams (ditch checks, ditch dikes). <a href=\"https://stormwater.pca.state.mn.us/index.php/Sediment_control_practices_-_Check_dams_(ditchttps://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/PA_NRCSConsumption/download?cid=nrcseprd526807&#x26;ext=pdfh_checks,_ditch_dikes\">https://stormwater.pca.state.mn.us/index.php/Sediment_control_practices_-_Check_dams_(ditchttps://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/PA_NRCSConsumption/download?cid=nrcseprd526807&#x26;ext=pdfh_checks,_ditch_dikes</a>)</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-13\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">13.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-13\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Biedenharn, D. S., Elliott, C. M. and Watson, C. C. (1997). THE WES STREAM INVESTIGATION AND STREAMBANK STABILIZATION HANDBOOK. <a href=\"https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/PA_NRCSConsumption/download?cid=nrcseprd526807&#x26;ext=pdf\">https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/PA_NRCSConsumption/download?cid=nrcseprd526807&#x26;ext=pdf</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-14\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">14.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-14\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Canilho, H., &#x26; Fael, C. (2018). Velocity Field Analysis of a Channel Narrowed by Spur-dikes to Maximize Power Output of In-stream Turbines. Journal of Sustainable Development of Energy, Water and Environment Systems, 6(3), 534-546. <a href=\"https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1029/2007WR006489\">https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1029/2007WR006489</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-15\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">15.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-15\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Burcharth, H. F., Zanuttigh, B., Andersen, T. L., Lara, J. L., Steendam, G. J., Ruol, P., ... &#x26; Nørgaard, J. Q. H. (2015). Innovative engineering solutions and best practices to mitigate coastal risk. In Coastal risk management in a changing climate (pp. 55-170). Butterworth-Heinemann. <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/local-scour\">https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/local-scour</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-16\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">16.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-16\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Giglou, A. N., Mccorquodale, J. A., &#x26; Solari, L. (2018). Numerical study on the effect of the spur dikes on sedimentation pattern. Ain Shams Engineering Journal, 9(4), 2057-2066.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-17\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">17.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-17\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  TRPA BMP Handbook (2014). Check dams. <a href=\"https://www.tahoebmp.org/Documents/BMPHandbook/Chapter%204/4.3/k_ChckDam.pdf\">https://www.tahoebmp.org/Documents/BMPHandbook/Chapter%204/4.3/k_ChckDam.pdf</a></p><!-- Images -->\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i1\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i1.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i1\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 1. Envirostruct Services. (2020). Scour Protection. <a href=\"http://estruct.com.au/waterways/revetment-walls/scour-protection/\">http://estruct.com.au/waterways/revetment-walls/scour-protection/</a> </p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i2\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i2.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i2\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 2. “Gulf of Mexico Wave Protection.” Contech Engineered Solutions, <a href=\"https://www.conteches.com/knowledge-center/case-studies/details/slug/gulf-of-mexico-wave-protection\">https://www.conteches.com/knowledge-center/case-studies/details/slug/gulf-of-mexico-wave-protection</a>. </p>\n      </li>\n      \n    </ol></div>","id":"f578c06a-426e-5ad3-9d4a-062a6cd6c531","frontmatter":{"date":"October 23, 2020","strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Scour Protection"}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/amphibious-buildings/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Amphibious Buildings"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/barrier-islands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Barrier Islands"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/beach-nourishment/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Beach Nourishment"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/breakwaters/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Breakwaters"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/coastal-wetlands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Coastal Wetlands"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-permits/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Permits"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-transfers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Transfers"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dikes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dry-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Dry Floodproofing"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dune-building-restoration/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dune Building / Restoration"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/easement-and-covenants/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Easement and Covenants"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/emergency-planning-and-preparedness/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Emergency Planning Preparedness"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/evacuation-routes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Evacuation Routes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/floodwalls/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Floodwalls"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/foreshore-tenure/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Foreshore Tenure"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/groynes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Groynes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-acquisition/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Acquisition"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-trust/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Trust"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/protected-area-zoning/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Protected Area Zoning"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/reef-systems/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Reef Systems"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Scour Protection"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Seawall"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/subdivision-regulation-and-development-control/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Subdivision Regulation and Development Control"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Warning System"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Wet Floodproofing"}}}]}},"pageContext":{"animationSlug":"//strategies/scour-protection/animation.*png/","slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/","foo":"bar","subpages":{"benefits":"<ul>\n<li>Longitudinal stones help to preserve significant amounts of the existing vegetation on a bank slope. It also encourages the growth of additional vegetation when the bank slope is stabilized. <sup id=\"fnref-14\"><a href=\"#fn-14\" class=\"footnote-ref\">14</a></sup></li>\n<li>The cost of protecting local scours is low. The maintenance requirements are also low.  Additionally, local scours are relatively easy to construct and adjust to minor scouring.  <sup id=\"fnref-15\"><a href=\"#fn-15\" class=\"footnote-ref\">15</a></sup></li>\n<li>Check dams help to promote infiltration which results in a reduction in channel erosion. Check dams also serve as traps for coarse sediments. <sup id=\"fnref-17\"><a href=\"#fn-17\" class=\"footnote-ref\">17</a></sup></li>\n<li>Check dams can reduce peak stormwater runoff.       </li>\n<li>Scour protection with lower levels of invert can improve discharge and reduce flooding levels.</li>\n</ul>","examples":["<h3>Gulf of Mexico Wave Protection</h3>\n<h4>Franklin County FL, USA</h4>\n<p>Along State Route 30/US 98 Coastline, beach erosion has been a major problem for more than 30 years.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> The highway is adjacent to the coastline and coastal erosion continues to destabilize the roadway. In response, the County decided to construct a revetment system along the coastline using a Contech ArmorFlex revetment system.<sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup> The ArmorFlex revetment system features interlocking blocks with a high unit weight that can withstand wave action and a porous system that promotes vegetation and habitat enhancement.<sup id=\"fnref-6\"><a href=\"#fn-6\" class=\"footnote-ref\">6</a></sup> </p>","<h3>Shubenacadie River</h3>\n<h4>Shubenacadie NS, Canada</h4>\n<p>During the 1980s and 1990s, the Nova Scotia Department of Agriculture and the Nova Scotia Department of Environment implemented several stream bank protection projects along the Shubenacadie River to mitigate the impacts of erosion on water quality and marine habitat.<sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup> Gabion baskets and mats were used in the stabilization of the river bank to protect the adjacent road.<sup id=\"fnref-8\"><a href=\"#fn-8\" class=\"footnote-ref\">8</a></sup> Other transportation infrastructures such as the Cheticamp Bridge that spans across the Shubenacadie River are also protected using similar gabion mats to protect the foundations of the bridge from erosion.<sup id=\"fnref-9\"><a href=\"#fn-9\" class=\"footnote-ref\">9</a></sup></p>"],"images":["<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 474px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/27e7a1f6869dbcb86bc19bb0fe6fdc9b/5595f/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 53.37837837837838%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/27e7a1f6869dbcb86bc19bb0fe6fdc9b/5595f/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/27e7a1f6869dbcb86bc19bb0fe6fdc9b/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/27e7a1f6869dbcb86bc19bb0fe6fdc9b/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/27e7a1f6869dbcb86bc19bb0fe6fdc9b/5595f/Figure2.png 474w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 474px) 100vw, 474px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nShoreline protection utilizing interlocking blocks <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/f3aa48927e2c6359cf4e9f5f40262f8c/4d4a2/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 35.810810810810814%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/f3aa48927e2c6359cf4e9f5f40262f8c/fcda8/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/f3aa48927e2c6359cf4e9f5f40262f8c/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/f3aa48927e2c6359cf4e9f5f40262f8c/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/f3aa48927e2c6359cf4e9f5f40262f8c/fcda8/Figure1.png 590w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/f3aa48927e2c6359cf4e9f5f40262f8c/4d4a2/Figure1.png 606w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nBridge scour protection <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>"],"types":"<ul>\n<li><strong>A spur dike</strong> is an elongated structure with one end on a bank of a stream and the other end projecting into the water. Spur dikes have been used widely for the protection of stream banks against erosion. They have also been used for the enhancement of aquatic habitats by creating stable pools in disturbed unstable streams. <sup id=\"fnref-10\"><a href=\"#fn-10\" class=\"footnote-ref\">10</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>A debris basin</strong> consists of an earth dam and a barrier constructed across a drainage way or other suitable location to collect sediment. Excess runoff from the dam occurs through spillways. Small pools of water flow through a sediment basin which captures and discharges runoff from adjacent lands. This allows larger silt particles to drop out into the pool. <sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>Check dams</strong> also referred to as ditch checks, dikes, and wattles, may be temporary or permanent linear structures that are installed in a perpendicular position to the flows emanating from drainage ditches, channels, and swales. Check dams help to reduce flow velocity and prevent the down-cutting of channels <sup id=\"fnref-12\"><a href=\"#fn-12\" class=\"footnote-ref\">12</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>Longitudinal stone toe</strong> is an alternative form of a windrow revetment where stones are placed along the existing streambed rather than on top of a bank. “The longitudinal stone toe is laced with a crown well below the top bank, either against the eroding bank line or a distance riverward of the high bank.” <sup id=\"fnref-13\"><a href=\"#fn-13\" class=\"footnote-ref\">13</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","summary":"<p>Scours are property-specific structural tools that are used to protect shoreline structures or building foundations from exposure to the corrosive effects of moving water. Scour protection is typically constructed from riprap or other types of material. The material is applied around the foundation of a structure to prevent erosion from wave action.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> Scours are commonly used in protecting the bases of bridge foundations, seawalls, coastlines near highways, rails, or pipelines.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> The strategy has limited protection as it only minimizes risk directly to the foundation of buildings and structures.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> </p>","challenges":"<ul>\n<li>Longitudinal stone toe protection only provides toe protection. It does not directly protect the mid and upper banks. Some erosion of the mid and upper bank areas may occur during long-duration, high energy flows, particularly, before these areas stabilize and become vegetated. <sup id=\"fnref-14\"><a href=\"#fn-14\" class=\"footnote-ref\">14</a></sup></li>\n<li>Local scours may be destabilized by a moderate flood before vegetation is re-established. <sup id=\"fnref-15\"><a href=\"#fn-15\" class=\"footnote-ref\">15</a></sup></li>\n<li>Spur dikes can lead to the contraction of the flow path which subsequently increases flow velocity in the contracted section. <sup id=\"fnref-16\"><a href=\"#fn-16\" class=\"footnote-ref\">16</a></sup></li>\n<li>Check dams can lead to a reduction in channel conveyance capacity thereby increasing the probability of overtopping. <sup id=\"fnref-17\"><a href=\"#fn-17\" class=\"footnote-ref\">17</a></sup></li>\n</ul>"},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/image2/"},"html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/9734286765287993f5603ace4a4517d9/c8e86/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 47.972972972972975%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/9734286765287993f5603ace4a4517d9/fcda8/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/9734286765287993f5603ace4a4517d9/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/9734286765287993f5603ace4a4517d9/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/9734286765287993f5603ace4a4517d9/fcda8/Figure2.png 590w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/9734286765287993f5603ace4a4517d9/c8e86/Figure2.png 758w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nExample of a basement with wet floodproofing <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/benefits/"},"html":"<ul>\n<li>Provides a prediction of the scale, timing, location, and likely damage that might be caused by an impending flood</li>\n<li>Provides timely notice for the release of gated dam water. This helps to, reduce      damage to communities and ecosystems</li>\n<li>Can serve as an adaptation measure at the individual and household level because data can be sent directly to individuals within a household. </li>\n<li>When implemented at the local and regional scales, it can reach those groups that are especially vulnerable to flooding. <sup id=\"fnref-12\"><a href=\"#fn-12\" class=\"footnote-ref\">12</a></sup></li>\n<li>Helps to improve disaster preparedness and hence can significantly reduce expensive disaster relief efforts.</li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":""}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3000541721"]}